Dorm Room Dilemma: How Students Retrieve Belongings from Campus

Allegheny College explains plan to get students back their dorm room belongings, some students have concerns.
Monday, May 11th 2020, 8:55 AM EDT
Updated:
Monday, May 11th 2020, 9:14 AM EDT
By Molly Somora

 

College students left campus in a rush at the start of the pandemic, not knowing when they'd be back.

Students at Allegheny College have packed full dorm rooms but, they won't be able to get their stuff themselves.

School officials say they have a plan in place to keep everyone as safe as they possible can.

Early last week, Allegheny College sent out a plan for students to retrieve their belongings from campus.

But, after all the response from students and families, school officials say they realized they didn't give enough information information about their decision making. 

"We need to do this retrieval process in a very condensed way and the most orderly way for us to do that is for us to organize the process instead of bringing lots of people in," says President Hillary Link. "We're talking about 1700 plus people, plus whoever they bring with them help pack, it's a lot of people."

The process now looks like this, a company will come in to pack each students dorm room while students are on Facetime with them, students can then choose if they want their items shipped to their house, pick up their boxes at an off campus location, or have them moved to their dorm room for next year.

President Hillary Link says the decision was made to keep everyone safe in hopes to be back on campus for the fall semester. 

"We took the really hard decision to say we need to take care of this, get people's belongings to them but, not have everybody come together on campus and potentially bring the virus, infect themselves, infect others," says Link. 

Some students reached out to Erie News Now about their concerns on getting their stuff out of their dorm rooms. 

 

"If somebody else is packing that up, how long is it going to take them to decide what person that belongs to? What did I miss? What didn't I get?," says Laura Morseman, Allegheny College parent. "That causes even more anxiety with everything that's going on."

Jamie Morseman and her mom Laura say their concerns about the plan Allegheny College has to get her items out of her dorm room.

Jamie says she left behind some special gifts, "all of this is fragile so I was mainly worried about the shipping process aspect of it, that it would be really easy to break because all of it's glass."

She says she doesn't want other packing up her belongings, "I would rather just head down there myself and get my stuff, even if it doesn't include me going inside."

Jamie's concerned things might end up missing during this process. 

"If someone wants to donate a certain object and yours accidentally gets put into their box, then your stuff is going to be gone as well," says Jamie. "It's not coming back."
